Suppose install path of VLD is `C:\Program Files (x86)\Visual Leak Detector`

Configure your project in order to use VLD when build *Debug* **Win32**:

1. Open &lt;kbd&gt;Project&lt;/kbd&gt;&lt;kbd&gt;Properties&lt;/kbd&gt;
2. Select Configuration: *Debug*, Platform: *Win32*
3. Open &lt;kbd&gt;Configuration Properties&lt;/kbd&gt;&lt;kbd&gt;VC++ Directories&lt;/kbd&gt;
4. Append &lt;kbd&gt;Include Directories&lt;/kbd&gt; with `C:\Program Files (x86)\Visual Leak Detector\include`
5. Append &lt;kbd&gt;Library Directories&lt;/kbd&gt; with `C:\Program Files (x86)\Visual Leak Detector\lib\Win32`

In similar way, for **Win64** you do:

1. Open &lt;kbd&gt;Project&lt;/kbd&gt;&lt;kbd&gt;Properties&lt;/kbd&gt;
2. Select Configuration: *Debug*, Platform: *Win64*
3. Open &lt;kbd&gt;Configuration Properties&lt;/kbd&gt;&lt;kbd&gt;VC++ Directories&lt;/kbd&gt;
4. Append &lt;kbd&gt;Include Directories&lt;/kbd&gt; with `C:\Program Files (x86)\Visual Leak Detector\include`
5. Append &lt;kbd&gt;Library Directories&lt;/kbd&gt; with `C:\Program Files (x86)\Visual Leak Detector\lib\Win64`

For *Release* configuration actions are identical, just choose *Release* on step (2).

Congratulations, now you can use VLD, just

```c++
#include &lt;vld.h&gt;
```

